## 5. Risk Assessment

| Risk | Severity | Affected Component | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| State machine transition logic divergence | 🔴 CRITICAL | All 7 use cases | Port identical guard logic; keep tests covering legacy routes throughout |
| 60s timer duplication | 🔴 HIGH | `InMemoryTimerAdapter` vs `bookingController` in-memory Map | Clean module has its own Map; legacy map remains. Both coexist — no conflict since clean routes are not yet served by `index.js` |
| `Booking.populate()` referencing wrong model name | 🟡 MEDIUM | `BookingSchema.js` model name | Use `mongoose.models.Booking \|\| mongoose.model('Booking', ...)` — same pattern as Worker |
| Socket event contract changes | 🟡 MEDIUM | Frontend WebSocket listeners | Adapter wraps same `socketService.js` — event names and payloads are copied verbatim |
| Telegram hardcoded chat ID | 🟡 MEDIUM | `CreateBookingUseCase` | Preserve exact hardcoded value from legacy controller until production config is established |
| Chat route on booking router | 🟡 MEDIUM | `GET /bookings/chats/:id` | Include `chatController.getChatHistory` in clean `bookingRoutes.js` |
| `paymentController` booking status gate | 🟡 MEDIUM | `verifyPaymentSignature` | `paymentController` uses `models/Booking.js` → proxy automatically resolves; no changes needed |
| Double Mongoose model registration | 🟢 LOW | `BookingSchema.js` | Idempotent guard eliminates risk |
| Test suite import of `routes/booking.js` | 🟢 LOW | Both test files | Legacy routes never removed; tests unaffected |

